exemnibus partibus] ‘from all quarters’r two Mss omit ex, but it is doubtful whether cineribus partibus could here be used in the sense of ‘on all accounts’3 cp, Cic. Fin. v. 93 vitam omnibus partibus plus habere semper beni quam mali.

1 legate] these three classes of officers, legates, centurious and military tribunes, formed the usual council of war.

3 multis rebus] ‘in many ways ’.

signa misisse] ‘had exhibited signs'; cp. Verg. Georg. 1. 119 haud obscura cadens mittet tibi signa Booten Lucr. 1. 874 fruges...mittere signum sanguinis: I hardly understand why Madvig Adv. 11. 165 objects to misisse here and wants to read dedisse or iam dedisse.

decederent] ‘were not coming down ’, notice change of tense from subvenissent.

regna servarent] owing to the narrow space the several legions were crowded together in confusion instead of being drawn up in line under their own colours.

4 iniquitatem lece] this phrase, which is frequent in Caesar, means ‘inequality of site' and is used where, of two opposing forces, one occupies a position of advantage, in respect of elevation, over the other.

alique loco] 1 see no reason for altering aliqunto aequo as Madvig does Adv. 11. 265, with the further change of tamen to hm.
